1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Stanford University

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:11,000
Alright, so let me just tell you a

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:15,000
little bit about the origins of string theory.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:19,000
The origins of string theory really were in hadron physics.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:22,000
They did not have to do with quantum gravity.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
They had to do with

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
protons, neutrons, mesons, particularly mesons.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:33,000
In fact, the theory was put forward at a

9
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:38,000
time when it really wasn't even known that for sure,

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,000
it was suspected, but it wasn't known for

11
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
sure that protons and neutrons, mesons and so forth,

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
had a quark content to them.

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,500
It was suspected that a

14
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:52,000
meson was a pair of quarks.

15
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
The idea of gluons did not yet exist.

16
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:57,000
The idea of gluons...

17
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Well, and...

18
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,000
Well, in fact, it actually did.

19
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:03,000
But nobody paid too much attention to it.

20
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Nembou had postulated something like it.

21
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:11,500
But gluons were not part of the standard discussion

22
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:17,000
of hadrons in, let's say, around 1969, 1968, 1970.

23
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,500
What was part of standard

24
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:26,000
hadron physics was an interesting fact

25
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:27,000
that the number of particles...

26
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:31,000
The number of particle states was large.

27
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:36,000
There was the proton and the neutron, of course.

28
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,500
I'm not interested in the

29
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:39,000
difference between proton and neutron.

30
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Just think of them as one thing, the nucleon.

31
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:44,000
And then there was another particle which

32
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,000
was very similar to the proton and neutron,

33
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
had a little more spin

34
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
and a little bit heavier mass.

35
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
And then there was another one above that with a

36
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
little bit heavier mass and a little bit larger spin.

37
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,000
People drew pictures, diagrams.

38
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,000
They were called Choufrouchi plots.

39
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Plots, not plots.

40
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
Plots, plots, plots.

41
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:08,000
And they were diagrams which indicated the

42
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,000
spectrum of objects like a proton, for example.

43
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
And they plotted horizontally here...

44
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Let's see.

45
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,500
They plotted vertically angular momentum and

46
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:24,000
horizontally the square of the mass.

47
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,500
Who decided to put the square of

48
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,000
the mass there instead of the mass?

49
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Nobody.

50
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
The diagrams had a nicer look

51
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
to them if you plotted mass squared.

52
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
And what was discovered experimentally...

53
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:41,000
This is an experimental fact...

54
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
I'm getting my P's and my F's screwed up today.

55
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
An experimental fact that the spectrum of particles...

56
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Okay, let's start with the proton.

57
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:51,000
That has half a unit of

58
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,000
spin and a mass of one.

59
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Okay.

60
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:56,500
And a mass of one in certain units, namely the

61
00:02:56,500 --> 00:03:00,000
unit in which the mass of the proton is one.

62
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
That's approximately one GeV.

63
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Incidentally, at that time, the GeV didn't exist.

64
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
It was the BeV for billion.

65
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Now it's giga.

66
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Okay.

67
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And so the proton and the neutron were over here.

68
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,500
A mass of one, mass squared of

69
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:23,000
one, and an angular momentum of a half.

70
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Then there's another particle

71
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:27,000
with angular momentum three halves.

72
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,500
These were fermions, and so their

73
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:32,000
angular momentum was quantized in half integers.

74
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:33,500
And so there was another one up

75
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:35,000
here with a little bit bigger mass.

76
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
Another one, another one, and another one.

77
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,500
And rather remarkably, these particles

78
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:45,000
all formed a straight line.

79
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:51,000
A straight line in the plot of L versus M.

80
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,500
Now I should tell you, when

81
00:03:53,500 --> 00:03:56,000
Chu and Frouchi first put this forward,

82
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
the logic of drawing a straight line,

83
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,000
there were only two points on this plot.

84
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,500
And they thought it was a theorem that through

85
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:07,000
any two points, you could draw a straight line.

86
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,500
Well, it is a theorem, but

87
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:12,000
these guys were not the smartest.

88
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,000
Well, they were pretty smart, but they...

89
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:18,000
And so they said, oh, there's two points.

90
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Let's draw a straight line through them.

91
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,500
And miraculously, as experiment went on, the

92
00:04:24,500 --> 00:04:28,000
additional particles all landed on the same line.

93
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
In M squared.

94
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
In M squared, yes, they actually said in M squared.

95
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,500
They plotted it as a function of M squared and

96
00:04:35,500 --> 00:04:38,000
L, and said, two points, let's draw a straight line.

97
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
And that worked out just fine.

98
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,500
But I mean, that explains why M squared is the axis

99
00:04:43,500 --> 00:04:47,000
there, because they're hypothesizing L is proportional to M squared somehow.

100
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
They were.

101
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Why did they postulate that?

102
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Because L is proportional to M.

103
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
They were lucky.

104
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
They were lucky, or else they had some deep...

105
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:02,000
No, it wasn't entirely luck, and it wasn't

106
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
entirely, and it wasn't a stupid guess either.

107
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
There were some interesting reasons for it.

108
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
But the same pattern held true for all hadrons, or

109
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
at least for all hadrons that have been studied in detail.

110
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
For example, the pi meson.

111
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:23,000
The pi meson also exists on a trajectory.

112
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:27,000
These are known as Regge trajectories,

113
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
R-E-G-G-E, for the Italian physicist Tullio Regge.

114
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
They're called Regge trajectories.

115
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,500
And if you plotted the meson spectrum, the meson

116
00:05:38,500 --> 00:05:43,000
spectrum, mesons are bosons, so the angular momenta were integers.

117
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,000
For example, the pi meson has almost zero mass.

118
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Its mass squared is even smaller than its mass.

119
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,000
It's true.

120
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
In units of a GeV.

121
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,500
Alright, so the pi meson was

122
00:05:57,500 --> 00:06:00,000
almost massless with almost zero angular momentum.

123
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,500
And then there's the next one

124
00:06:02,500 --> 00:06:05,000
up, I forget what it's called.

125
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
I don't remember what the next one is called.

126
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:10,000
I used to know, but I don't remember anymore.

127
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
The next one up, and the next one

128
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:18,000
up, and five, six, seven particles along a trajectory.

129
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Like that.

130
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,500
The rho meson, which was another

131
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:27,000
meson, which starts with angular momentum one.

132
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Also same pattern.

133
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:31,500
And what's more, all of these

134
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:34,000
trajectories were parallel to each other.

135
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:37,500
They were parallel to each other, which said, whatever this

136
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:41,000
M squared thing is, it takes exactly the same energy.

137
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Well, not exactly, but approximately the

138
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,000
same energy to increase the M squared

139
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
by when you, to increase M

140
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
squared when you increase the angular momentum.

141
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
In other words, the spectrum was quantized.

142
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
Of course it was quantized.

143
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
These were particles, and this is quantum mechanics.

144
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,500
The spectrum was quantized, but in each case,

145
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:07,000
the same relationship between L and M squared

146
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,500
and the same quantum jump in M

147
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:12,000
squared when you increased L by one unit.

148
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
One unit now means in

149
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
units of Planck's constant, of course.

150
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Okay.

151
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,500
So there's something going on that was giving rise to

152
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:26,000
large numbers of particles of higher and higher angular momentum.

153
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Higher angular momentum is not that uncommon.

154
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,000
You take a basketball.

155
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
You leave it at rest.

156
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:37,000
That basketball has a certain energy and therefore

157
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:40,000
a certain mass, and you could plot it someplace.

158
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
And now you spin the basketball.

159
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Give it one unit of Planck's angular momentum.

160
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
That's not easy to do, incidentally.

161
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
But when it has some

162
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
angular momentum, it will be rotating.

163
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
It will have some rotational energy.

164
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,500
So if you increase its angular momentum by one unit,

165
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:59,000
you will have to increase its energy by a little bit.

166
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
Tiny, tiny bit for a basketball.

167
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
And you can keep increasing

168
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
the angular momentum of the basketball.

169
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:09,000
As you do so, the energy will increase.

170
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
In fact, it will not look like a straight line.

171
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
It will look like a curve.

172
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And it will end somewheres.

173
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Why does the curve end?

174
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:25,000
The curve ends simply because at some angular velocity, the centrifugal

175
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:30,000
forces are so large that the basketball will just be torn apart.

176
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,500
So it ends someplace at some high

177
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:37,000
angular momentum, which represents the strength of materials.

178
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:42,000
How strong is whatever basketballs are made out of.

179
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
So trajectories like that were not unusual.

180
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:47,000
You can plot them for atoms.

181
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Atoms also have the property that as you increase

182
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:53,000
their angular momentum, you increase their energy, their mass.

183
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:56,000
Energy and mass being the same thing.

184
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:00,000
But again, for an atom, there's only so much

185
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:04,000
mass you can give it before you ionize the atom.

186
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:07,500
So what was unusual, particularly unusual, and again,

187
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:11,000
incidentally, factually, I'm not going to go into that.

188
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:12,500
But what was unusual, particularly unusual, and again,

189
00:09:12,500 --> 00:09:14,000
incidentally, factually, I'm not going to go into that.

190
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:14,500
But what was unusual, particularly unusual, and again,

191
00:09:14,500 --> 00:09:15,000
incidentally, factually, I'm not going to go into that.

192
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,500
And again, incidentally, for atoms,

193
00:09:16,500 --> 00:09:18,000
they would not be straight lines.

194
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
But what was unusual here was the simplicity

195
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
of the formula or the simplicity of the observation.

196
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:25,000
Rather straight lines.

197
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:28,000
I mean they were all

198
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:31,000
straight and parallel to each other.

199
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:32,000
And...

200
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:36,000
When you say parallel, I mean, how do you mean?

201
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
I mean that if you were to plot the

202
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
meson, or the baryon, or the proton, or the neutron,

203
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:43,000
I mean, how do you mean...

204
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
the limazon or the romezon, its

205
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
excited states would form the same line.

206
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,080
In other words, you take a set of

207
00:09:52,080 --> 00:09:55,160
particles, a family of particles, same slope, same slope,

208
00:09:55,160 --> 00:09:59,000
and it was called the universal regeslope.

209
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,620
Same for bosons and fermions, same

210
00:10:03,620 --> 00:10:08,240
for different families of bosons and fermions.

211
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:11,220
Now this is strictly for those objects which

212
00:10:11,220 --> 00:10:14,200
are hadrons, those things made up out of quarks

213
00:10:14,200 --> 00:10:18,420
and gluons, which we now today recognize

214
00:10:18,420 --> 00:10:22,640
as being made up of quarks and gluons.

215
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:24,640
That was one observation.

216
00:10:24,640 --> 00:10:27,060
The implication of this observation was fairly

217
00:10:27,060 --> 00:10:29,480
clear, even though it was misinterpreted at

218
00:10:29,480 --> 00:10:32,240
the time in many quarters.

219
00:10:32,240 --> 00:10:34,260
It was fairly clear.

220
00:10:34,260 --> 00:10:37,220
It said that hadrons were composite.

221
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:38,220
That you could spin them up.

222
00:10:38,220 --> 00:10:41,200
This is not something you can do with an electron.

223
00:10:41,200 --> 00:10:44,330
There is no excited state of an electron

224
00:10:44,330 --> 00:10:47,460
with higher angular momentum, at least not within

225
00:10:47,460 --> 00:10:50,600
current experimental bounds.

226
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:53,860
So electrons are like points.

227
00:10:53,860 --> 00:10:56,720
You can't spin a point.

228
00:10:56,720 --> 00:10:58,860
Spinning a point doesn't mean anything.

229
00:10:58,860 --> 00:11:02,880
Turning a point, you can spin a lump.

230
00:11:02,880 --> 00:11:08,180
So somehow these objects were not simple point particles.

231
00:11:08,180 --> 00:11:10,620
That was the message that should have been,

232
00:11:10,620 --> 00:11:13,060
and in many quarters was taken from this.

233
00:11:13,060 --> 00:11:17,340
And in fact that they had a stretchability

234
00:11:17,340 --> 00:11:21,620
that from this picture you could deduce if

235
00:11:21,620 --> 00:11:24,929
you wanted, and we will, we will, you could

236
00:11:24,929 --> 00:11:28,239
deduce the fact that they deform as they spin.

237
00:11:28,239 --> 00:11:31,020
You wouldn't, it's not obvious from here, but you can.

238
00:11:31,020 --> 00:11:33,160
All right, but there was something else.

239
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:35,129
There was another observation, which

240
00:11:35,129 --> 00:11:37,099
was a very bizarre observation.

241
00:11:37,099 --> 00:11:38,060
Let's see.

242
00:11:38,060 --> 00:11:40,699
Let me describe it to

243
00:11:40,699 --> 00:11:43,339
you in terms of meson-meson scattering.

244
00:11:43,339 --> 00:11:46,419
Let's take meson-meson, and for

245
00:11:46,419 --> 00:11:49,500
particular let's take pi-meson, pi-meson scattering.

246
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:51,280
Here's a pion coming in.

247
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:54,099
A pi-meson, let's call it pi.

248
00:11:54,099 --> 00:11:55,529
It doesn't matter whether

249
00:11:55,529 --> 00:11:56,959
it's pi-plus, pi-minus, doesn't matter.

250
00:11:56,959 --> 00:12:01,140
And it scatters off another pi-meson.

251
00:12:01,140 --> 00:12:04,320
There is a particle called the romezon,

252
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:07,500
which, while it's not a composite, it's a

253
00:12:08,060 --> 00:12:10,560
composite of two pi-mesons.

254
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:13,439
Two pi-mesons can come together at a vertex

255
00:12:13,439 --> 00:12:16,319
in a Feynman diagram and make a romezon.

256
00:12:16,319 --> 00:12:18,380
Let's make the romezon like that.

257
00:12:18,380 --> 00:12:19,869
We're going to talk, we may or

258
00:12:19,869 --> 00:12:21,359
may not talk more about these mesons.

259
00:12:21,359 --> 00:12:23,849
It's not important, the idea is important,

260
00:12:23,849 --> 00:12:26,339
but the particular names are not important.

261
00:12:26,339 --> 00:12:27,439
Romezon.

262
00:12:27,439 --> 00:12:32,249
And then that pi-meson could, then that romezon

263
00:12:32,249 --> 00:12:37,060
could materialize as a pair of pi-mesons again,

264
00:12:37,060 --> 00:12:37,939
this being a Feynman diagram.

265
00:12:37,940 --> 00:12:40,740
A conventional Feynman diagram.

